7). Split train and test Dataset

###Grab all the developed cells (presence)
newUrban <- SL %>%
  filter(urbanChg == TRUE)

###Grab all the nondeveloped and not previously urban cells (absence)
nonUrban <- SL %>%
  filter(urbanChg == FALSE)

###Get a random sample of the absence data  
### that is twice as large as the presence data
index <- sample(1:nrow(nonUrban), (round(nrow(newUrban)* 2)))
SLsampleUrban <- nonUrban[index, ]

### combine the orginal presence and absence data
SLsample <- rbind(SLsampleUrban, newUrban)

index <- sample(1:nrow(SLsample), (round(nrow(SLsample)* 0.01)))
SLsample <- SLsample[index, ]

SLsample <- SLsample %>%
  mutate(urbanChgTF = ifelse(urbanChg == TRUE , 1, 
               ifelse(urbanChg == FALSE, 0, NA)))


SLsample <- SLsample %>% dplyr::mutate(id = row_number())
train <- SLsample %>% sample_frac(.70)
test  <- anti_join(SLsample, train, by = 'id')

4). Model Performance Using ROC curve the evaluate the performance of Random Forest model in this case, and we can see the auc of this curve is 0.974, which is very close to 1, that means the model has a goodness of fit in urban change simulation using these four variables.

library(ROCR)
## Warning: package 'ROCR' was built under R version 4.3.2
# plot a ROC curve for a single prediction run
# and color the curve according to cutoff.
pred <- prediction(predict(fit,newdata=test), test$urbanChg)
perf <- performance(pred,"tpr","fpr")
plot(perf,colorize=TRUE)

## A simpler way to understand these result is to calculate the
## area under the curve(AUC). The closer this number is to 1, the
## better your model fit
auc_ROCR <- performance(pred, measure = "auc")
auc_ROCR <- auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
auc_ROCR
## [1] 0.9727233

5). Importance of variables

Variable importance in a Random Forest model is measured by looking at how much prediction error increases when data for that variable is permuted, maintaining all others constant. Using varImpPlot function to plot the importance(IncNodePurity) of the four variables, and we can see that “road distance” will explain the most variance, and then DEM, Park distance and least is wasterDist.

imp <- importance(fit)
imp <- (imp - min(imp)) / (max(imp) - min(imp))
imp <- as.data.frame(imp)
imp$varnames <- rownames(imp)
rownames(imp) <- NULL  

ggplot(imp, aes(x=reorder(varnames, IncNodePurity), y=IncNodePurity)) + 
  geom_point() +
  geom_segment(aes(x=varnames,xend=varnames,y=0,yend=IncNodePurity)) +
  scale_color_discrete(name="Variable Group") +
  ylab("IncNodePurity") +
  xlab("Variable Name") +
  coord_flip()+
  ggtitle("Variable Importance of Random Forest")

2). Data Pre-processing

Normalize total number of Flickr photographs by population, and omit NA values and calculate the Z-score(This allows for equitable comparisons between different variables when determining clusters, particularly critical in k-means clustering where the algorithm is distance-based)

amenData$SocialNorm <- amenData$Nat_Flickr/(amenData$serPop10 + 1)
amenData$HousingChg <- amenData$Urb2011 - amenData$Urb2001

amenDataDF<-amenData[,c("SocialNorm", "HousingChg", "HotelTOT", "Urb2001","HistStruc", "HistObject","HistSite", "Histdistr", "Histbuild","ser00publi", "serhous90" )]

## make sure there are no missing data
amenDataDF <- na.omit(amenDataDF)
amenDataDF <- as.data.frame(amenDataDF)[1:11]
## calculate z-scores for the dataset
db_scaled <- scale(amenDataDF)

3). Determine number of clusters Try multiple possible cluster sizes to see what number of clusters works best, we can see that there is a sudden drop of within groups sum of squares when the clustering number changes from 2 to 3, so we can use 3 as the number of clustering.

wss <- (nrow(db_scaled)-1)*sum(apply(db_scaled,2,var))
for (i in 2:15) wss[i] <- sum(kmeans(db_scaled,
   centers=i)$withinss)
## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 3998550)

## Warning: Quick-TRANSfer stage steps exceeded maximum (= 3998550)

We can see that the historical characteristics of the US has a difference basically between eastern part and western part. Another thing that needs noticing is that the western part’s cluster is more continuous while the eastern part is more fragmented, it might be because of the terrain of eastern part is mainly highland or mountainous area under the effect of the Great Divide, those continuous part might stand for natural(Cowboy? Indigenous People?) based historical culture.
